div.p:
                 Ceballinus could not have deſir'd a greater proof as to the truth of what he had ſaid; and Philotas juſtify'd him to his own condemnation, looſing him from his Chains to put them on himſelf. The King, who whilſt Philotas was abſent, had complain'd of his Ingratitude with tears, could not diſſemble his reſentment when he ſaw him. Wherefore with anger in his looks he ſpake thus; 
                    Ceballinus deſerves extream puniſhment, if he has bin three days without making me acquainted with a Conſpiracy againſt my Perſon; but if he gave you information as ſoon as ever he knew it, your ſilence is yet more

inexcuſable, conſidering the great Teſtimonies of my Truſt and Affection. I cannot imagine what ſhould induce you to ſo horrid a Treaſon. I have yet ſome ſentiments of Affection for you; If you are innocent, Ceballinus deſerves to die; if guilty, make an ingenuous confeſſion, I am not inexorable.
